<!-- ════ GLOSSARY MODAL ════ -->
<div class="modal-bg" id="glossaryModal" onclick="if(event.target===this)closeGlossary()">
  <div class="modal">
    <div class="gloss-modal-head">
      <button class="modal-close" onclick="closeGlossary()">×</button>
      <h2>Glossary</h2>
      <p class="lead" style="margin-bottom:14px">Plain definitions for the terms used across the portal.</p>
      <div style="position:relative">
        <i class="ti ti-search" style="position:absolute;left:12px;top:50%;transform:translateY(-50%);color:var(--ink-3);font-size:16px;pointer-events:none"></i>
        <input class="gloss-search" id="glossSearch" type="text" placeholder="Search terms…" autocomplete="off" oninput="glossFilter(this.value)">
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="gloss-modal-body">
    <div class="gloss-no-results" id="glossNoResults">No terms match your search.</div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="alice"><div class="gloss-term">ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed)</div><div class="gloss-def">A United Way framework that identifies households earning above the federal poverty line but below the basic cost of living for their county — meaning they are employed and not "poor" by official measures, yet cannot afford housing, food, childcare, transportation, healthcare, and a smartphone plan simultaneously. In North Meck, ALICE households are the hidden gap between prosperity and poverty.</div><div class="gloss-src">United Way ALICE Project</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="alice-threshold"><div class="gloss-term">ALICE Threshold</div><div class="gloss-def">The minimum income a household needs to cover a bare-bones budget for housing, food, childcare, transportation, healthcare, and technology in a given county. It is calculated by United Way for every county in the U.S. and is consistently higher than the federal poverty line — in Mecklenburg County it is roughly 2–3× the FPL for a family of four.</div><div class="gloss-src">United Way ALICE Project</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="acs"><div class="gloss-term">American Community Survey (ACS)</div><div class="gloss-def">The U.S. Census Bureau's largest ongoing survey, producing yearly estimates of income, rent, housing, and demographics for communities nationwide. Most figures on this site come from the ACS.</div><div class="gloss-src">U.S. Census Bureau</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="ami"><div class="gloss-term">Area Median Income (AMI)</div><div class="gloss-def">The midpoint income for households in a metro area, set annually by HUD. In Charlotte-Mecklenburg the 2025 median is $112,200 for a family of four. Housing programs use percentages of AMI (30%, 50%, 80%) to set eligibility.</div><div class="gloss-src">HUD FY25 Income Limits</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="cost-burdened"><div class="gloss-term">Cost-burdened</div><div class="gloss-def">A household spending more than 30% of its gross monthly income on housing (rent or mortgage plus utilities). At this level, households often struggle to cover food, healthcare, and other essentials.</div><div class="gloss-src">HUD definition</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="data-equity"><div class="gloss-term">Data equity</div><div class="gloss-def">An approach to collecting, analyzing, and presenting data that actively includes marginalized communities and corrects for historical bias. The CRF program applies a data-equity framework to all of its research.</div><div class="gloss-src">Urban Institute Data Equity Framework, 2021</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="eviction-filing"><div class="gloss-term">Eviction filing</div><div class="gloss-def">A legal document a landlord files to remove a tenant. It appears on a tenant's record even if the case is later dismissed, making future housing harder to secure. In FY25, 52,625 eviction cases were filed in Mecklenburg County.</div><div class="gloss-src">Mecklenburg County FY25</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="fmr"><div class="gloss-term">Fair Market Rent (FMR)</div><div class="gloss-def">HUD's estimate of the gross rent for a modestly priced unit in a metro area. FY25 Charlotte-Meck: one-bedroom $1,647/month, two-bedroom $1,824/month.</div><div class="gloss-src">HUD FY25 FMR, Charlotte-Concord-Gastonia MSA</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="fpl"><div class="gloss-term">Federal Poverty Line (FPL)</div><div class="gloss-def">The federal government's official income threshold below which a household is classified as living in poverty. For 2024 it is about $31,200 for a family of four. Critics argue the FPL was designed in the 1960s based on food costs alone and dramatically understates the true cost of living in high-cost suburbs like North Mecklenburg.</div><div class="gloss-src">U.S. Dept. of Health &amp; Human Services</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="gini"><div class="gloss-term">Gini Coefficient</div><div class="gloss-def">A statistical measure of income inequality within a population. It ranges from 0 (perfect equality — everyone earns the same) to 1 (maximum inequality — one person earns everything). The U.S. national average is roughly 0.40. Cornelius registered 0.52–0.53 in recent years, approaching levels seen in large cities and indicating a wide gap between its highest- and lowest-income residents.</div><div class="gloss-src">U.S. Census Bureau ACS</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="homeownership"><div class="gloss-term">Homeownership rate</div><div class="gloss-def">The share of households that own, rather than rent, their home. Differences in homeownership by race are a core measure of housing equity and of wealth built up over generations.</div><div class="gloss-src">U.S. Census ACS</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="voucher"><div class="gloss-term">Housing Choice Voucher (Section 8)</div><div class="gloss-def">A federal program that helps low-income households afford private-market rent. The household generally pays about 30% of its income toward rent and the voucher covers the rest.</div><div class="gloss-src">HUD</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="housing-wage"><div class="gloss-term">Housing wage</div><div class="gloss-def">The hourly pay a full-time worker needs to afford a modest rental home without spending more than 30% of their income on rent. For the Charlotte–Mecklenburg metro in 2025, the one-bedroom housing wage is $31.67 an hour.</div><div class="gloss-src">NLIHC Out of Reach 2025</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="hud"><div class="gloss-term">HUD</div><div class="gloss-def">The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, the federal agency that funds housing assistance and sets the income limits, Fair Market Rents, and affordability standards used throughout this portal.</div><div class="gloss-src">U.S. Dept. of Housing &amp; Urban Development</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="msa"><div class="gloss-term">Metro area (MSA)</div><div class="gloss-def">A Metropolitan Statistical Area, a Census-defined region made up of a city and the surrounding communities tied to it economically. Regional figures here use the Charlotte–Concord–Gastonia MSA.</div><div class="gloss-src">U.S. Census Bureau</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="noah"><div class="gloss-term">Naturally Occurring Affordable Housing (NOAH)</div><div class="gloss-def">Privately owned, unsubsidized rentals that are affordable because of their age or condition, not a government program. In Mecklenburg County, low-cost rentals (under $800/month) fell from 36% to just 8% of all rental stock between 2015 and 2024.</div><div class="gloss-src">Charlotte-Mecklenburg State of Housing, 2025</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="redlining"><div class="gloss-term">Redlining</div><div class="gloss-def">A discriminatory practice, widespread from the 1930s onward, in which banks and the government withheld mortgages and investment from neighborhoods because of their racial makeup. Its effects on homeownership and wealth are still visible today.</div><div class="gloss-src">Mapping Inequality, University of Richmond</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="severely-cost-burdened"><div class="gloss-term">Severely cost-burdened</div><div class="gloss-def">Spending more than 50% of gross monthly income on housing, leaving very little for anything else and sharply raising the risk of eviction or homelessness.</div><div class="gloss-src">HUD definition</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="survival-budget"><div class="gloss-term">Survival budget</div><div class="gloss-def">United Way's term for the bare-minimum household spending plan used to set the ALICE Threshold. It includes only non-negotiable monthly costs — a modest apartment, groceries, childcare, a car, basic healthcare, and a smartphone — with nothing left for savings, debt repayment, or emergencies.</div><div class="gloss-src">United Way ALICE Project</div></div>
    <div class="gloss" data-term="two-gen"><div class="gloss-term">Two-generation model</div><div class="gloss-def">A service approach that supports children and the adults in their lives at the same time, pairing early education with job training, food assistance, and financial coaching, so a whole family can move toward stability together.</div><div class="gloss-src">Ada Jenkins Center</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
